Bluetongue, Cyprus
---------------
Information received on 22 Dec 2010 from Dr Pavlos Toumazos, Director
of Veterinary Services, Veterinary Services , Ministry of
Agriculture, Natural Resources and Environment, Nicosia, Cyprus

Summary

Report type: Follow-up report No. 3
Start date: 22 Oct 2010
Date of 1st confirmation of the event: 22 Oct 2010
Report date 22 Dec 2010
Date submitted to OIE: 22 Dec 2010
Reason for notification Reoccurrence of a listed disease
Date of previous occurrence: 2007
Manifestation of disease: Sub-clinical infection
Causal agent: Bluetongue virus
Serotype: 16
Nature of diagnosis: Laboratory (basic)
This event pertains to the whole country

New outbreaks:
[Sub-clinical cases in holdings of sheep or cattle, which are
included in the monthly surveillance programme for bluetongue. For
detailed information, please refer to the above URL which includes a map].

Summary of outbreaks
Total outbreaks: 3
Total animals affected
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Destroyed / Slaughtered
Cattle / 233 / 10 / 0 / 0 / 0
Sheep / 220 / 4 / 0 / 0 / 0

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>

[Previous to the 6 outbreaks of BTV-16 in Greek sheep on Lesvos
described in the above follow-up report, clinical cases of BTV-16
have been reported by Greece, since the beginning of November 2010,
from several North and South Aegean islands as follows: Lesvos (12
outbreaks), Samos (1), Kos (1) and Rodos (2). Some of those islands
(e.g. Lesvos, Samos and Kos) are adjacent to the Turkish coast, where
similar cases are assumed to have taken place. In fact, Turkey
reported an outbreak of BTV-16 in sheep which had taken place in May
2010 in Karaoz, Aksu, Antalya (see, with map, at
<http://www.oie.int/wahis/public.php?page=single_report&pop=1&reportid=9834>).

Since BT is transmitted by culicoides, midges which are known to be
bourne by wind to significant distances, it is rather likely that the
virus may have been circulating during recent months also within
other territories in the eastern Mediterranean and the Middle East
(e.g. Syria, Lebanon, Israel and Jordan), and that clinical cases in
susceptible animals may have been seen. Information, including data
-- if available -- on the BT serotypes involved, is requested. - Mod.AS]
